2.body: At Incite Literacy , our purpose is simple: return agency to the learner . Incite Literacy is unscripted, real-world learning driven by curiosity, relevance, and purpose. Curiosity, creativity, and exploration have been suffocated‚Äîshrunk down to fit inside rubrics and GPA formulas meant for a world that no longer exists. At Incite Literacy, we believe: Learning is a process ‚Äîand it should be owned by the learner. Agency is not optional ‚Äîit‚Äôs the foundation of future-ready learning. Growth isn‚Äôt standardized ‚Äîit‚Äôs self-driven, iterative, and personal. We‚Äôre not here to prescribe your path. We‚Äôre here to help you discover what matters to you ‚Äîand give you the tools to build from there. We won‚Äôt tell you what to do. We‚Äôll help you figure out what you want to do. We won‚Äôt tell you how to do it. The challenge (and the joy) is in the process. We won‚Äôt tell you when you‚Äôre done. You decide when the work is real, relevant, and ready. This is your learning. Own it. Shape it. Incite it.

28.body: Project Based Learning vs. Design Thinking: Side-by-Side Comparison Key Differences Both Project Based Learning (PBL) and Design Thinking (DT) provide structured processes that guide learning. PBL as a Framework : Provides a structured sequence ( problem introduction ‚Üí inquiry ‚Üí creation ‚Üí presentation ) that helps students develop solutions systematically. DT as a Framework : Provides a step-by-step process ( empathize ‚Üí define ‚Üí ideate ‚Üí prototype ‚Üí test ) for problem-solving and innovation.
28.breadcrumbs: How You Learn ¬ª project-based-learning-and-design-thinking ¬ª Project Based Learning and Design Thinking as Frameworks
28.title: Project Based Learning and Design Thinking as Frameworks

30.body: PBL is anchored in a driving question and emphasizes process over product . It focuses on producing a final product or solution based on a defined problem. Design Thinking starts with empathy and revolves around iterative innovation . It focuses on understanding users and iterating solutions, often leading to multiple prototypes rather than a single finished product. PBL fits well in academic settings , while DT thrives in creative, entrepreneurial, or user-focused problem-solving . At Incite Literacy , both are blended to empower learners to solve real problems for real people ‚Äîstarting from structure (PBL) and evolving toward creativity (DT) .
30.title: Key Differences

69.body: We don‚Äôt use them at the same time‚Äîwe use them in stages. While they share common values, they serve different purposes: Project-Based Learning (PBL) provides structure. Students learn by doing‚Äîworking through meaningful, real-world projects from start to finish. Design Thinking (DT) adds a creative process. Students use empathy, research, prototyping, and feedback to design solutions that matter. Phase 1: Project-Based Learning (PBL) We start with PBL to help students get used to thinking creatively, building confidence, and working through structured, real-world projects. It‚Äôs a great starting point for those coming from traditional classrooms or just getting started. Phase 2: Hybrid Approach In this middle stage, students start influencing the process‚Äîchoosing topics or shaping how they approach a challenge. This phase blends the structure of PBL with the creative flexibility of Design Thinking. Phase 3: Design Thinking (DT) Once students are ready, they use the full Design Thinking framework to lead their own projects‚Äîindependently identifying problems, exploring solutions, and building meaningful outcomes. Used together, they create a powerful experience: students don‚Äôt just complete projects‚Äîthey solve problems that make an impact. This progression helps students build the mindset and skills they need to confidently own their learning journey.
